  "prompt": "How can you determine the ionic charge of sodium?",
  "response": "To determine the ionic charge of sodium, you can follow these steps:\n\n1. **Identify the Element**: Sodium is a chemical element with the symbol Na and atomic number 11. This means that a neutral sodium atom has 11 protons and 11 electrons.\n\n2. **Understand Electron Configuration**: The electron configuration of sodium is \\( 1s^2 2s^2 2p^6 3s^1 \\). This shows that sodium has one electron in its outermost shell (the 3rd shell).\n\n3. **Ionic Behavior**: Elements typically form ions to achieve a full outer electron shell, which is more stable. For alkali metals like sodium, which are in Group 1 of the periodic table, they tend to lose the single electron in their outer shell.\n\n4. **Losing Electrons**: When sodium loses this one outer electron, it becomes positively charged because it has more protons (11) than electrons (10). Thus, the ionic charge of sodium is \\( +1 \\).\n\n5. **Conclusion**: Therefore, the ionic charge of sodium when it forms an ion is \\( \\text{Na}^+ \\), indicating it has a charge of +1.",
